The article discusses how the Bipartisan Infrastructure Law aims to invest in the conservation of and access to public lands in order to build a better America. Senior officials, including Mitch Landrieu and Sarah Greenberger, highlight the President's commitment to partnering with states, conservation groups, hunters, anglers, tribes, and others to conserve America's lands and waters. The law includes funding for ecosystem restoration, resilience, invasive species prevention, and native vegetation restoration, as well as cleaning up legacy pollution. The Department of the Interior recently announced the distribution of a record $1.5 billion in Wildlife and Sport Fish Restoration Program allocations to state wildlife agencies. Landrieu emphasizes that these grants, along with other investments from the Bipartisan Infrastructure Law, will contribute significantly to collaborative conservation efforts.